## Conclusion ## 

In this investigation, the compromise had already occurred. The attacker's first observed action was SAMR reconnaissance at packet 848. Following this, the attacker attempted lateral movement by creating Desktop.ini and Autorun.inf files at packets 1854 and 1856 respectively. Both attempts failed.
The attacker then downloaded a payload at packet 2439, initiated by a GET request for the file ooiwy.pdf at packet 2127, using an outdated and insecure User-Agent (curl/7.55.1). The server returned what appeared to be a PDF but contained an MZ executable. After exporting and hashing the file, the SHA256 hash returned a rating of 60/72 on VirusTotal. Cross-referencing on MalwareBazaar confirmed the malware as TrickBot.
The attacker then performed a GET request to 50.19.119.155 (Host: api.ipify.org), which is not inherently malicious on its own. However, the response came from a server identifying itself as "Cowboy" — an unusual server identifier — and the response body contained the victim's public IP address: 173.66.46.97 (0/94 on VirusTotal). This GET was performed by TrickBot to obtain the victim's public IP before establishing C2 communication.
At packet 5091, data exfiltration occurred from 10.8.19.101 → 103.148.41.195 via:
http://103.148.41.195:443/rob124/DESKTOP-M1TFHB6_W10019043.0CB9C3AE3FA9B1267DF
The URL itself reveals the attacker's intent. Analysis of the POST body confirmed the following data was exfiltrated: System Processes, System Info, and Local Machine Data. The "Cowboy" server confirmed receipt of the data.
Two active C2 channels were identified, used by the attacker to send instructions to the victim's device. Both channels remained active for the majority of the PCAP, from packet 3240 to packet 17312. Confirmed as active C2 due to consistent content length across all packets and consistent use of port 443.
